Understanding Inference

Zach Smith

Suppose have a dataset \(X\) that is distributed

\[ \mu = 3 \\ \sigma = 10 \\ X \sim Normal(\mu, \sigma ) \]

set.seed(1)

N <- 60
mu <- 3
sigma <- 10
x <- rnorm(N, mu, sigma)

hist(x)

If \(\mu\) is unknown how do we perform inference?

  1. MLE
  2. MCMC
  3. Variational Inference

MLE

To perform MLE we find \(\hat{\mu}\) by taking the average of the data points \(\frac{\sum x_i}{N}\)

mu_hat <- mean(x)
se <- sigma / sqrt(N)
mean(x)
## [1] 4.076164
estimates <- data.frame(method = "MLE", mu_hat = mu_hat, se = se)
knitr::kable(estimates)
method mu_hat se
MLE 4.076164 1.290994 
x1 <- seq(-20, 20, by=0.01) + mu
plot(x = x1, y = dnorm(x1, mu_hat, se), type="l")
abline(v = mu)
abline(v = mu_hat, lty=2)
legend("topleft", legend=c("mu", "mu_hat"), lty=c(1,2))

Conjugate

prior_mu <- 2
prior_sigma <- 2

mu_hat <- (prior_mu / prior_sigma^2 + sum(x) / sigma^2) / (1 / prior_sigma^2 + N / sigma^2)
se <- sqrt(1 / (1 / prior_sigma^2 + N / sigma^2))

estimates <- rbind(estimates, data.frame(method = "Conjugate", mu_hat = mu_hat, se = se))
knitr::kable(estimates)
method mu_hat se
MLE 4.076164 1.290994
Conjugate 3.465527 1.084652

MCMC

Suppose we have some prior information on the true value of mu

\[ \mu \sim N(2, 2) \\ \sigma = 10 \\ X \sim N(\mu, \sigma ) \]

And our statistics professors never taught us about conjugate priors, so we perform MCMC inference.

This will not give us an analytical solution, but instead samples from the posterior \(p(\mu | X=x)\)

prior_mu <- 2
prior_sigma <- 2

# we need a proposal distribution 
# very tiny jumps == high acceptance rate but slow mixing
jump_sigma <- 1
rproposal <- function(mu_) rnorm(1, mu_, jump_sigma) 

# function to calculate the posterior likelihood (proportional)
dposterior <- function(x, mu, sigma, prior_mu, prior_sigma) {
  log_likelihood <- dnorm(mu, prior_mu, prior_sigma, log = TRUE) + sum(dnorm(x, mu, sigma, log = TRUE))
  log_likelihood
}

mu_1 <- rnorm(1, prior_mu, prior_sigma)
old_likelihood <- dposterior(x, mu_1, sigma, prior_mu, prior_sigma)

mus <- c()

# run metropolis hastings MCMC
iters <- 10000
for(i in 1:iters){
  # propose new mu
  mu_2 <- rproposal(mu_1)
  new_likelihood <- dposterior(x, mu_2, sigma, prior_mu, prior_sigma)
  acceptance_ratio <- exp(new_likelihood - old_likelihood)
  # accept or reject
  u <- runif(1)
  mu_1 <- ifelse(u <= acceptance_ratio, mu_2, mu_1)
  mus <- c(mus, mu_1)
  old_likelihood <- new_likelihood
}

# thin the draws
  acor <- acf(mus) # autocorrelation

mus_thin <- mus#[seq(1, length(mus), by = acor$lag[which.min(acor$acf)])]

Lets inspect the posterior draws

mu_hat <- mean(mus_thin)
se <- sd(mus_thin)

estimates <- rbind(estimates, data.frame(method = "MCMC", mu_hat = mu_hat, se = se))
knitr::kable(estimates)
method mu_hat se
MLE 4.076164 1.290994
Conjugate 3.465527 1.084652
MCMC 3.434981 1.361317 
plot(density(mus), xlim = c(min(x1), max(x1)), main = "Posterior Distribution for u")
abline(v = mu)
abline(v = mu_hat, lty=2)
legend("topleft", legend=c("mu", "mu_hat"), lty=c(1,2))

Variational Inference

We are impatient with MCMC so perhaps we would like to turn this into an optimization problem.

We specify a distribution \(q(\mu )\) to approximate the posterior \(p(\mu |X)\)

n_draws = 1000

kl_divergence <- function(x, sigma, prior_mu, prior_sigma, n_draws){
  function(posterior_vals){
    #take samples from approximate distribution
    z <- rnorm(n_draws, posterior_vals[1], posterior_vals[2])
    #calculate elbo
    elbo <- sapply(z, function(z_i){
      sum(dnorm(x, z_i, sigma, log = TRUE) ) + dnorm(z_i, prior_mu, prior_sigma, log = TRUE) - dnorm(z_i, posterior_vals[1], posterior_vals[2], log = TRUE)
    })
    mean(elbo)
  }
}

to_optimize <- kl_divergence(x, sigma, prior_mu, prior_sigma, n_draws)

# grid search
future::plan(future::multicore, workers = future::availableCores())
to_search <- expand.grid(seq(-2, 8, by = 1), seq(0.1, 10, by = 1))
to_search$elbo <- furrr::future_map_dbl(1:nrow(to_search), ~to_optimize(c(to_search[.,1], to_search[.,2])), .options = furrr::furrr_options(seed=1))
to_search <- setNames(to_search, c("mu_hat", "se", "elbo"))

best_val <- to_search[which.max(to_search$elbo),]
estimates <- rbind(estimates, data.frame(method = "VI", mu_hat = best_val$mu_hat, se = best_val$se))
knitr::kable(estimates)
method mu_hat se
MLE 4.076164 1.290994
Conjugate 3.465527 1.084652
MCMC 3.434981 1.361317
VI 3.000000 1.100000 
to_search %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = mu_hat, y = se, fill = elbo)) +
  geom_tile() +
  geom_point(data = best_val, aes(x = mu_hat, y = se), col="red")

x1 <- seq(-20, 20, by=0.01) + mu
plot(x = x1, y = dnorm(x1, best_val$mu_hat, best_val$se), type="l")
abline(v = mu)
abline(v = best_val$mu_hat, lty=2)
legend("topleft", legend=c("mu", "mu_hat"), lty=c(1,2))

# coordinate ascent
post_mu <- 0
post_sigma <- 5

iters <- 10000
h <- 1e-2
step_size <- 1e-3
steps <- as.data.frame(matrix(0, nrow = iters, ncol = 2)) %>%  setNames(c("mu", "sigma"))
for(i in 1:iters){
  #step mu
  gradient <- (to_optimize(c(post_mu + h, post_sigma)) - to_optimize(c(post_mu, post_sigma))) / h
  post_mu <- post_mu + gradient * step_size
  #step sigma
  gradient <- (to_optimize(c(post_mu, post_sigma + h)) - to_optimize(c(post_mu, post_sigma))) / h
  post_sigma <- post_sigma + gradient * step_size
  
  steps[i,] <- c(post_mu, post_sigma)
}
to_search %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_tile(aes(x = mu_hat, y = se, fill = elbo)) +
  geom_path(data = steps, aes(x = mu, y = sigma), col="red")
